A man has been charged with assaulting Aaron Ramsdale at the north London derby on Sunday. Joseph Watts, 35, of Hackney was charged on Tuesday with assault by beating, entering an area next to a playing area and throwing a missile onto a football pitch, according to the Met Police. Both offences are contrary to the Football (Offences) Act 1991.   Mr Watts is due to appear at Highbury Magistrates’ Court on February 17, the Met said. The force said in a statement: "The Met's Football Investigations Team were assisted in their enquiries by Tottenham Hotspur Football Club." After Sunday's game, the Football Association "strongly condemned" an incident involving Arsenal's goalkeeper. It came after his side's victory over Tottenham. Tottenham said after the match that violence in any form has no place in football.   The Football Association "strongly" condemned the incident at the Premier League fixture between Spurs and Arsenal. In a statement issued after the match, the Premier League said: "There is no place in football for acts of violence." The Professional Footballers' Association has said players have a right to be safe in their place of work and that as the players' union it treated the incident as a priority issue. It added in a statement: "We will be continuing to work with the authorities to demand that players and staff are better protected in their place of work." 